  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "Alright, I have this limit to solve:\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}\\left(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x\\right)\n\\]\n\nAt first glance, it seems a bit tricky because I have a cube root of a polynomial and then adding \\( x \\). I need to simplify this expression to find the limit as \\( x \\) approaches infinity. Let's break it down step by step.\n\n### Step 1: Understand the Expression\n\nFirst, let's look at the expression inside the limit:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x\n\\]\n\nAs \\( x \\) approaches infinity, both \\( x^2 \\) and \\( x^3 \\) are going to infinity, but \\( x^3 \\) grows much faster than \\( x^2 \\). So, \\( x^2 - x^3 \\) is going to negative infinity. Taking the cube root of that will still go to negative infinity. Adding \\( x \\) (which is going to positive infinity) makes it indeterminate. So, I need to manipulate the expression to find the limit.\n\n### Step 2: Factor Out the Dominant Term\n\nTo simplify the cube root, I'll factor out \\( x^3 \\) from \\( x^2 - x^3 \\):\n\n\\[\nx^2 - x^3 = -x^3 + x^2 = x^3\\left(-1 + \\frac{x^2}{x^3}\\right) = x^3\\left(-1 + \\frac{1}{x}\\right)\n\\]\n\nSo, the cube root becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{x^3\\left(-1 + \\frac{1}{x}\\right)} = x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{-1 + \\frac{1}{x}}\n\\]\n\nNow, the original expression \\( \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x \\) can be rewritten as:\n\n\\[\nx \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{-1 + \\frac{1}{x}} + x = x \\left( \\sqrt[3]{-1 + \\frac{1}{x}} + 1 \\right)\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Simplify the Expression Inside the Parentheses\n\nLet's focus on \\( \\sqrt[3]{-1 + \\frac{1}{x}} + 1 \\). As \\( x \\to \\infty \\), \\( \\frac{1}{x} \\to 0 \\), so this becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{-1} + 1 = -1 + 1 = 0\n\\]\n\nBut wait, multiplying by \\( x \\) which is going to infinity, we have \\( x \\cdot 0 \\), which is indeterminate (since \\( x \\cdot 0 \\) can approach any number depending on how fast \\( x \\) grows compared to the approaching zero). Therefore, I need a better approximation.\n\n### Step 4: Use Binomial Approximation\n\nFor small \\( \\delta \\), \\( \\sqrt[3]{1 + \\delta} \\approx 1 + \\frac{\\delta}{3} \\). However, in our case, we have \\( \\sqrt[3]{-1 + \\frac{1}{x}} \\). Let's set \\( y = \\frac{1}{x} \\), so as \\( x \\to \\infty \\), \\( y \\to 0 \\). Then the expression becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{-1 + y}\n\\]\n\nTo approximate \\( \\sqrt[3]{-1 + y} \\), I can use the binomial expansion for cube roots:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{-1 + y} = -1 + \\frac{y}{3} + \\text{higher order terms}\n\\]\n\nSince \\( y \\to 0 \\), higher order terms become negligible, so:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{-1 + y} \\approx -1 + \\frac{y}{3}\n\\]\n\nSubstituting back \\( y = \\frac{1}{x} \\):\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{-1 + \\frac{1}{x}} \\approx -1 + \\frac{1}{3x}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Substitute the Approximation Back\n\nNow, substitute this approximation into the original expression:\n\n\\[\nx \\left( \\sqrt[3]{-1 + \\frac{1}{x}} + 1 \\right) \\approx x \\left( -1 + \\frac{1}{3x} + 1 \\right) = x \\left( \\frac{1}{3x} \\right) = \\frac{1}{3}\n\\]\n\nAs \\( x \\to \\infty \\), the higher order terms we neglected earlier become insignificant, so the expression simplifies to \\( \\frac{1}{3} \\).\n\n### Step 6: Conclude the Limit\n\nTherefore, the limit is:\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}\\left(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x\\right) = \\frac{1}{3}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\frac{1}{3}}\n\\]",
